Corruption is a global issue, and both India and other nations have implemented various anti-corruption policies. Here's an overview of key initiatives:

India's Anti-Corruption Policies:

India has a complex legal and institutional framework aimed at combating corruption. Key components include:   

The Prevention of Corruption Act, 1988 (PCA):
This is the primary legislation addressing corruption by public servants.   
It criminalizes bribery, misuse of official power, and other corrupt practices.   
The Right to Information Act, 2005 (RTI):
This empowers citizens to access government information, promoting transparency and accountability.   
It is a powerful tool to expose corruption.
The Prevention of Money Laundering Act, 2002 (PMLA):
This targets the laundering of proceeds of crime, including those derived from corruption.   
The Lokpal and Lokayuktas Act, 2013:
This established the Lokpal (at the national level) and Lokayuktas (at the state level) to investigate allegations of corruption against public officials.   
Central Vigilance Commission (CVC):
This is an apex Indian government body created to address governmental corruption.   
Anti-Corruption Policies Abroad:

Many countries and international organizations have also implemented anti-corruption measures:

United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC):
This is a global treaty that provides a framework for countries to combat corruption.   
It covers areas such as prevention, criminalization, international cooperation, and asset recovery.   
OECD Anti-Bribery Convention:
This focuses on combating bribery of foreign public officials in international business transactions.   
United States Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA):
This prohibits U.S. companies and individuals from bribing foreign officials.   
United Kingdom Bribery Act 2010:
This has very broad reaching anti bribery rules.
Transparency International:
This is a global non-governmental organization that publishes the Corruption Perceptions Index and advocates for anti-corruption measures.   
Key Trends:

Increasing emphasis on transparency and accountability.
Strengthening of legal frameworks and enforcement mechanisms.
Greater international cooperation in combating cross-border corruption.   
The growing role of technology in detecting and preventing corruption.
